      "key": {
        "uuid": "a0ed487c_3448b290",
        "filename": "util/stream/zlib_output_stream_test.cc",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 100,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-08-23T20:36:58Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "In Crashpad tests, whenever a gtest assertion like this is inside a loop, we always include a hint to indicate where things are in the loop iteration. That way, if a gtest assertion fails, it’s clear which iteration is the problem. Troubleshooting can be much easier if you know whether it’s the first time through the loop or last time, or what the value iterated was. So, if you look around, you’ll find that what we’d do here (given the loop structure I suggested above) is:\n\n  #include \"base/stringprintf.h\"\n\n  const size_t write_length \u003d kWriteLengths[index];\n  SCOPED_TRACE(base::StringPrintf(\"index %zu, write_length %zu\", index, write_length));\n\nI think we can use %zu everywhere in cross-platform code now. That used to not be the case, as the Microsoft CRT didn’t support the ‘z’ length modifier. However, if you do find that %zu isn’t accepted uniformly, you’d #include \"base/format_macros.h\" and use \"%\" PRIuS. There are ample examples of this in our codebase.\n\nThis also applies to the other loop that contains a gtest assertion within, at line 137.",
      "revId": "c10db1c52f4bcdbf8102dc47501eeedd412e6c53",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
